{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0165A2kj6rbUhWDtZDLCdu5C","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Title Extractor Failure Analysis — Iteration 3\n     2→\n     3→## Failures Summary\n     4→\n     5→| File | Expected | Got |\n     6→|------|----------|-----|\n     7→| ARAYES SHRAK | `ARAYES SHRAK` | `ARAYES` |\n     8→| Baked Eggs with Feta… | `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` | `` |\n     9→| FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS | `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` | `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` |\n    10→| SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D) | `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` | `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` |\n    11→\n    12→---\n    13→\n    14→## Pattern 1: Substring deduplication removes the correct multi-line join\n    15→\n    16→**Affects: ARAYES SHRAK, SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS, Baked Eggs**\n    17→\n    18→### The bug\n    19→\n    20→The dedup rule at line 335 reads:\n    21→\n    22→```ts\n    23→// b is shorter and is contained in a: remove a when b is equally or more title-like\n    24→if (aLower.includes(bLower) && b.text.length < a.text.length && b.rawScore >= a.rawScore) return true;\n    25→```\n    26→\n    27→This fires whenever a shorter candidate is a substring of a longer one and the shorter candidate's rawScore is ≥ the longer. The intention is to drop a bloated join when the clean short title is already captured. In practice it does the opposite: it removes the *complete* title (the multi-line join) in favour of a *partial* first line, because partial titles almost always score ≥ the full join in embedding space.\n    28→\n    29→### Why partial scores ≥ full join\n    30→\n    31→The embedding model measures semantic similarity to \"recipe name, dish title…\". A partial title like `ARAYES` or `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` already carries the full semantic signal of a recipe title. Adding `SHRAK` or `/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` does not increase title-similarity — it may even dilute it slightly by introducing unfamiliar tokens. So rawScore(partial) ≥ rawScore(join) is the common case, not an edge case.\n    32→\n    33→### Per-file breakdown\n    34→\n    35→**ARAYES SHRAK**\n    36→The OCR split the title onto two lines:\n    37→```\n    38→ARAYES        ← line 1\n    39→SHRAK         ← line 2\n    40→```\n    41→`buildCandidates` correctly builds the 2-line join `ARAYES SHRAK`, which qualifies as the `firstStructuralHeading` (+0.10 structural bonus, +0.08 ALL_CAPS bonus). However, dedup runs on `rawScore` only, ignoring bonuses. Since `rawScore(\"ARAYES\") ≥ rawScore(\"ARAYES SHRAK\")`, the join is discarded and `ARAYES` alone is returned.\n    42→\n    43→**SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)**\n    44→The OCR split the title onto two lines:\n    45→```\n    46→SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK       ← line 54\n    47→/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)      ← line 55\n    48→```\n    49→`SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` qualifies as `firstStructuralHeading` (every word has ≥4 alpha letters; the `firstStructuralHeading` check excludes the `/` line). The 2-line join `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` does NOT qualify as `firstStructuralHeading` because `/` has 0 alpha letters, failing the `every word ≥4 letters` guard. So the join receives +0.08 ALL_CAPS bonus only, while the partial receives +0.18. The dedup then removes the join (rawScore of partial ≥ rawScore of join), and the partial wins by its structural bonus — which was never a fair contest because the join was penalised before dedup even ran.\n    50→\n    51→**Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander**\n    52→The OCR split the title onto two lines:\n    53→```\n    54→Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce   ← line 1\n    55→& Coriander                                  ← line 2\n    56→```\n    57→The 2-line join passes all hard filters (54 chars, no measurements, no garbling). Dedup removes it because `rawScore(\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\") ≥ rawScore(full join)`. The remaining candidates are the partial first line and `& Coriander` as an isolated fragment. `& Coriander` alone has very low title-similarity (a connector fragment starting with `&` scores poorly against the title reference). After threshold filtering, it is likely dropped. The result depends on whether the partial line alone clears the `max(0.08, bestScore * 0.8)` threshold; if it doesn't — because the file has few candidates and the best score is low — the function returns `undefined`, explaining the empty string output. This is the most severe failure: no title extracted at all.\n    58→\n    59→---\n    60→\n    61→## Pattern 2: Second recipe title falls below threshold on multi-recipe pages\n    62→\n    63→**Affects: FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS**\n    64→\n    65→The file contains two distinct recipes on the same page. Both headings are present:\n    66→\n    67→```\n    68→FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS       ← line 16 (of 43)\n    69→FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS     ← line 29 (of 43)\n    70→```\n    71→\n    72→Both pass `passesHardFilters`. Both are ALL_CAPS with ≥2 words of ≥4 letters, so `allCapsSelected.length >= 2` should fire and keep both.\n    73→\n    74→The failure is that `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` does not appear in `selected` at the scoring stage. The likely cause is the threshold: `Math.max(0.08, bestScore * 0.8)`.\n    75→\n    76→- `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` is at relative position ~0.37 → positionFactor ≈ 1.075 (boost applied).\n    77→- `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` is at relative position ~0.67 → positionFactor = 1.0 (no boost, position > 0.5).\n    78→\n    79→If `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` is the highest-scoring candidate, the threshold is set at `0.8 × its score`. Any candidate whose rawScore is slightly lower (including a second ALL_CAPS heading of comparable but not identical quality) may fall below this threshold and never reach the multi-title guard.\n    80→\n    81→The position factor creates an asymmetry: it boosts the first title's final score, raising the threshold, which then excludes the later title. This is a self-defeating interaction — the position bonus intended to prefer early titles inadvertently raises the bar high enough to exclude valid second titles.\n    82→\n    83→---\n    84→\n    85→## Common Themes\n    86→\n    87→1. **The dedup logic is inverted for multi-line joins.** The rule \"shorter substring wins on equal rawScore\" was designed to clean up redundant joins, but it systematically destroys the *correct* complete title when a partial title is equally title-like in embedding space. Practically all real-world split titles are affected. The fix needs to account for the case where the longer candidate is the structurally correct result (i.e. it received a bonus for a reason).\n    88→\n    89→2. **Continuation fragments starting with punctuation (`&`, `/`, `+`) break multi-line joining.** These fragments individually score near-zero for title similarity. When the dedup removes the joined candidate, nothing reassembles the full title. The algorithm has no mechanism to recognise that `& Coriander` and `/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` are continuations rather than standalone candidates.\n    90→\n    91→3. **`firstStructuralHeading` bonus is computed before dedup, but dedup ignores it.** For ARAYES SHRAK and SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS, the join earns or should earn the structural bonus — yet dedup discards it using rawScore alone. The bonus signals that the join is the correct title, but that signal is never consulted during deduplication.\n    92→\n    93→4. **The position-factor × threshold interaction punishes late-appearing titles.** On multi-recipe pages, the first heading earns a position bonus that raises the threshold, making it harder for subsequent headings to survive. The multi-title guard (`allCapsSelected.length >= 2`) is correct in intent but never gets to fire because the second candidate is eliminated upstream at the threshold step.\n    94→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5176536c-f5cc-4676-9e25-3601b34e1824","uuid":"9024414f-1a6c-4fa2-94e6-e743d4e06fe7","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/3-a5a0dca/feedback.md","content":"# Title Extractor Failure Analysis — Iteration 3\n\n## Failures Summary\n\n| File | Expected | Got |\n|------|----------|-----|\n| ARAYES SHRAK | `ARAYES SHRAK` | `ARAYES` |\n| Baked Eggs with Feta… | `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` | `` |\n| FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS | `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` | `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` |\n| SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D) | `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` | `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` |\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 1: Substring deduplication removes the correct multi-line join\n\n**Affects: ARAYES SHRAK, SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS, Baked Eggs**\n\n### The bug\n\nThe dedup rule at line 335 reads:\n\n```ts\n// b is shorter and is contained in a: remove a when b is equally or more title-like\nif (aLower.includes(bLower) && b.text.length < a.text.length && b.rawScore >= a.rawScore) return true;\n```\n\nThis fires whenever a shorter candidate is a substring of a longer one and the shorter candidate's rawScore is ≥ the longer. The intention is to drop a bloated join when the clean short title is already captured. In practice it does the opposite: it removes the *complete* title (the multi-line join) in favour of a *partial* first line, because partial titles almost always score ≥ the full join in embedding space.\n\n### Why partial scores ≥ full join\n\nThe embedding model measures semantic similarity to \"recipe name, dish title…\". A partial title like `ARAYES` or `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` already carries the full semantic signal of a recipe title. Adding `SHRAK` or `/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` does not increase title-similarity — it may even dilute it slightly by introducing unfamiliar tokens. So rawScore(partial) ≥ rawScore(join) is the common case, not an edge case.\n\n### Per-file breakdown\n\n**ARAYES SHRAK**\nThe OCR split the title onto two lines:\n```\nARAYES        ← line 1\nSHRAK         ← line 2\n```\n`buildCandidates` correctly builds the 2-line join `ARAYES SHRAK`, which qualifies as the `firstStructuralHeading` (+0.10 structural bonus, +0.08 ALL_CAPS bonus). However, dedup runs on `rawScore` only, ignoring bonuses. Since `rawScore(\"ARAYES\") ≥ rawScore(\"ARAYES SHRAK\")`, the join is discarded and `ARAYES` alone is returned.\n\n**SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)**\nThe OCR split the title onto two lines:\n```\nSAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK       ← line 54\n/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)      ← line 55\n```\n`SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` qualifies as `firstStructuralHeading` (every word has ≥4 alpha letters; the `firstStructuralHeading` check excludes the `/` line). The 2-line join `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` does NOT qualify as `firstStructuralHeading` because `/` has 0 alpha letters, failing the `every word ≥4 letters` guard. So the join receives +0.08 ALL_CAPS bonus only, while the partial receives +0.18. The dedup then removes the join (rawScore of partial ≥ rawScore of join), and the partial wins by its structural bonus — which was never a fair contest because the join was penalised before dedup even ran.\n\n**Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander**\nThe OCR split the title onto two lines:\n```\nBaked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce   ← line 1\n& Coriander                                  ← line 2\n```\nThe 2-line join passes all hard filters (54 chars, no measurements, no garbling). Dedup removes it because `rawScore(\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\") ≥ rawScore(full join)`. The remaining candidates are the partial first line and `& Coriander` as an isolated fragment. `& Coriander` alone has very low title-similarity (a connector fragment starting with `&` scores poorly against the title reference). After threshold filtering, it is likely dropped. The result depends on whether the partial line alone clears the `max(0.08, bestScore * 0.8)` threshold; if it doesn't — because the file has few candidates and the best score is low — the function returns `undefined`, explaining the empty string output. This is the most severe failure: no title extracted at all.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 2: Second recipe title falls below threshold on multi-recipe pages\n\n**Affects: FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS**\n\nThe file contains two distinct recipes on the same page. Both headings are present:\n\n```\nFINNISH MILK FLATBREADS       ← line 16 (of 43)\nFINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS     ← line 29 (of 43)\n```\n\nBoth pass `passesHardFilters`. Both are ALL_CAPS with ≥2 words of ≥4 letters, so `allCapsSelected.length >= 2` should fire and keep both.\n\nThe failure is that `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` does not appear in `selected` at the scoring stage. The likely cause is the threshold: `Math.max(0.08, bestScore * 0.8)`.\n\n- `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` is at relative position ~0.37 → positionFactor ≈ 1.075 (boost applied).\n- `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` is at relative position ~0.67 → positionFactor = 1.0 (no boost, position > 0.5).\n\nIf `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` is the highest-scoring candidate, the threshold is set at `0.8 × its score`. Any candidate whose rawScore is slightly lower (including a second ALL_CAPS heading of comparable but not identical quality) may fall below this threshold and never reach the multi-title guard.\n\nThe position factor creates an asymmetry: it boosts the first title's final score, raising the threshold, which then excludes the later title. This is a self-defeating interaction — the position bonus intended to prefer early titles inadvertently raises the bar high enough to exclude valid second titles.\n\n---\n\n## Common Themes\n\n1. **The dedup logic is inverted for multi-line joins.** The rule \"shorter substring wins on equal rawScore\" was designed to clean up redundant joins, but it systematically destroys the *correct* complete title when a partial title is equally title-like in embedding space. Practically all real-world split titles are affected. The fix needs to account for the case where the longer candidate is the structurally correct result (i.e. it received a bonus for a reason).\n\n2. **Continuation fragments starting with punctuation (`&`, `/`, `+`) break multi-line joining.** These fragments individually score near-zero for title similarity. When the dedup removes the joined candidate, nothing reassembles the full title. The algorithm has no mechanism to recognise that `& Coriander` and `/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` are continuations rather than standalone candidates.\n\n3. **`firstStructuralHeading` bonus is computed before dedup, but dedup ignores it.** For ARAYES SHRAK and SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS, the join earns or should earn the structural bonus — yet dedup discards it using rawScore alone. The bonus signals that the join is the correct title, but that signal is never consulted during deduplication.\n\n4. **The position-factor × threshold interaction punishes late-appearing titles.** On multi-recipe pages, the first heading earns a position bonus that raises the threshold, making it harder for subsequent headings to survive. The multi-title guard (`allCapsSelected.length >= 2`) is correct in intent but never gets to fire because the second candidate is eliminated upstream at the threshold step.\n","numLines":94,"startLine":1,"totalLines":94}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015SyxCciueCVvBKWUDMKiwv","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/**\n     2→ * Title Extraction\n     3→ * Extracts potential recipe title from OCR text using heuristics or semantic embeddings\n     4→ */\n     5→\n     6→import { cosineSimilarity } from \"./embeddings\";\n     7→\n     8→export type EmbedFn = (text: string) => Promise<Array<number>>;\n     9→\n    10→const TITLE_REFERENCE =\n    11→  \"recipe name, dish title, name of the food, nazwa przepisu, nazwa dania\";\n    12→const HEADER_REFERENCE =\n    13→  \"ingredients list, cooking directions, section heading, składniki, przygotowanie, sposób wykonania\";\n    14→const NOISE_REFERENCE =\n    15→  \"page number, table of contents, book footer, garbled text\";\n    16→\n    17→/**\n    18→ * Measurement units commonly found in ingredient lists\n    19→ */\n    20→const MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS = [\n    21→  \"cup\",\n    22→  \"cups\",\n    23→  \"tbsp\",\n    24→  \"tsp\",\n    25→  \"tablespoon\",\n    26→  \"teaspoon\",\n    27→  \"oz\",\n    28→  \"lb\",\n    29→  \"gram\",\n    30→  \"grams\",\n    31→  \"kg\",\n    32→  \"ml\",\n    33→  \"liter\",\n    34→  \"pinch\",\n    35→  \"dash\",\n    36→  \"handful\",\n    37→];\n    38→\n    39→/**\n    40→ * Patterns that identify recipe metadata lines (not titles)\n    41→ */\n    42→const METADATA_PATTERNS = [\n    43→  /^(SERVES?|MAKES?|YIELDS?)\\b/i,\n    44→  /^(PREP(ARATION)?|COOK(ING)?|PROOF|RISING|FERMENTATION|REST(ING)?)\\s*(AND\\s*)?(COOK(ING)?)?\\s*TIME/i,\n    45→  /^SAMPLE\\s+SCHEDULE\\b/i,\n    46→  /^BULK\\s+FERMENTATION\\b/i,\n    47→  /^(THIS\\s+RECIPE\\s+)?MAKES\\b/i,\n    48→];\n    49→\n    50→/**\n    51→ * Single-word non-title words — standalone OCR fragments unlikely to be recipe titles\n    52→ */\n    53→const NON_TITLE_WORDS = new Set([\n    54→  \"the\", \"and\", \"for\", \"but\", \"not\", \"you\", \"all\", \"can\", \"are\", \"was\",\n    55→  \"has\", \"his\", \"her\", \"its\", \"our\", \"who\", \"how\", \"may\", \"new\", \"now\",\n    56→  \"old\", \"see\", \"way\", \"did\", \"get\", \"let\", \"say\", \"she\", \"too\", \"use\",\n    57→  \"buns\", \"with\",\n    58→]);\n    59→\n    60→function looksLikeIngredient(line: string): boolean {\n    61→  const lowerLine = line.toLowerCase();\n    62→  return MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => lowerLine.includes(pattern));\n    63→}\n    64→\n    65→function startsWithNumber(line: string): boolean {\n    66→  return /^\\s*\\d/.test(line);\n    67→}\n    68→\n    69→function isAllCaps(line: string): boolean {\n    70→  const letters = line.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\");\n    71→  return letters.length > 0 && letters === letters.toUpperCase();\n    72→}\n    73→\n    74→function looksLikeMetadata(text: string): boolean {\n    75→  return METADATA_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => pattern.test(text.trim()));\n    76→}\n    77→\n    78→function isLikelyGarbled(text: string): boolean {\n    79→  const letters = text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\");\n    80→  if (letters.length < 2) return true;\n    81→\n    82→  // Check vowel ratio — English/Polish text typically has 30–50% vowels\n    83→  const vowels = letters.replace(/[^aeiouAEIOUyYąęóĄĘÓ]/g, \"\").length;\n    84→  const vowelRatio = vowels / letters.length;\n    85→  if (vowelRatio < 0.15 || vowelRatio > 0.85) return true;\n    86→\n    87→  // Single orphaned word ≤3 letters that isn't a common word\n    88→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n    89→  const COMMON_SHORT = new Set([\n    90→    \"the\", \"and\", \"for\", \"but\", \"not\", \"you\", \"all\", \"can\", \"had\", \"her\",\n    91→    \"was\", \"one\", \"our\", \"out\", \"are\", \"has\", \"his\", \"how\", \"its\", \"may\",\n    92→    \"new\", \"now\", \"old\", \"see\", \"way\", \"who\", \"did\", \"get\", \"let\", \"say\",\n    93→    \"she\", \"too\", \"use\",\n    94→  ]);\n    95→  if (words.length === 1 && letters.length <= 3 && !COMMON_SHORT.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) {\n    96→    return true;\n    97→  }\n    98→\n    99→  // Recipe titles never start with a lowercase letter\n   100→  if (/^[a-z]/.test(text.trim())) {\n   101→    return true;\n   102→  }\n   103→\n   104→  // Mid-text sentence boundary (\". \" followed by a letter) — body text fragment spliced from multiple sentences\n   105→  const trimmed = text.trim();\n   106→  if (/\\.\\s+[a-zA-Z]/.test(trimmed) && !trimmed.endsWith(\")\")) {\n   107→    return true;\n   108→  }\n   109→\n   110→  // Multi-word candidate containing a garbled OCR fragment: a short lowercase word that isn't a known short word\n   111→  if (words.length >= 2) {\n   112→    const commonShort2 = new Set([\n   113→      \"a\", \"i\", \"of\", \"or\", \"to\", \"in\", \"on\", \"is\", \"it\", \"an\",\n   114→      \"as\", \"at\", \"by\", \"do\", \"go\", \"if\", \"no\", \"so\", \"up\", \"we\",\n   115→      \"w\", \"z\",  // Polish prepositions\n   116→    ]);\n   117→    const hasGarbledWord = words.some(\n   118→      (w) =>\n   119→        /^[a-z]/.test(w) &&\n   120→        w.replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\").length <= 2 &&\n   121→        !commonShort2.has(w.toLowerCase())\n   122→    );\n   123→    if (hasGarbledWord) {\n   124→      return true;\n   125→    }\n   126→  }\n   127→\n   128→  return false;\n   129→}\n   130→\n   131→function passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n   132→  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n   133→  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n   134→  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n   135→  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n   136→  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n   137→  // Single-word non-title fragments\n   138→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n   139→  if (words.length === 1 && NON_TITLE_WORDS.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) return false;\n   140→  return true;\n   141→}\n   142→\n   143→/**\n   144→ * Detect initial burst of short garbled lines.\n   145→ * Returns the index of the first non-garbled or long line.\n   146→ */\n   147→function findBurstEnd(lines: Array<{ text: string }>): number {\n   148→  let i = 0;\n   149→  while (i < lines.length && lines[i].text.length < 20 && isLikelyGarbled(lines[i].text)) {\n   150→    i++;\n   151→  }\n   152→  return i;\n   153→}\n   154→\n   155→function wordCount(text: string): number {\n   156→  return text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.length > 0).length;\n   157→}\n   158→\n   159→/**\n   160→ * Build candidate strings from lines: single lines plus multi-line joins (2-3 consecutive).\n   161→ * Skips initial burst of short garbled lines. Scans all remaining lines. Caps at 25.\n   162→ */\n   163→function buildCandidates(\n   164→  lines: Array<string>\n   165→): Array<{ text: string; position: number }> {\n   166→  const nonEmptyLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n   167→\n   168→  for (let i = 0; i < lines.length; i++) {\n   169→    const trimmed = lines[i].trim();\n   170→    if (trimmed.length > 0) {\n   171→      nonEmptyLines.push({ text: trimmed, index: i });\n   172→    }\n   173→  }\n   174→\n   175→  const burstEnd = findBurstEnd(nonEmptyLines);\n   176→  const candidates: Array<{ text: string; position: number }> = [];\n   177→  const seen = new Set<string>();\n   178→\n   179→  for (let i = burstEnd; i < nonEmptyLines.length; i++) {\n   180→    const line = nonEmptyLines[i];\n   181→\n   182→    // Single line\n   183→    if (passesHardFilters(line.text)) {\n   184→      const norm = line.text.toLowerCase();\n   185→      if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n   186→        seen.add(norm);\n   187→        candidates.push({ text: line.text, position: line.index });\n   188→      }\n   189→    }\n   190→\n   191→    // 2-line join\n   192→    if (i + 1 < nonEmptyLines.length) {\n   193→      const joined2 = `${line.text} ${nonEmptyLines[i + 1].text}`;\n   194→      if (passesHardFilters(joined2)) {\n   195→        const norm = joined2.toLowerCase();\n   196→        if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n   197→          seen.add(norm);\n   198→          candidates.push({ text: joined2, position: line.index });\n   199→        }\n   200→      }\n   201→    }\n   202→\n   203→    // 3-line join\n   204→    if (i + 2 < nonEmptyLines.length) {\n   205→      const joined3 = `${line.text} ${nonEmptyLines[i + 1].text} ${nonEmptyLines[i + 2].text}`;\n   206→      if (passesHardFilters(joined3)) {\n   207→        const norm = joined3.toLowerCase();\n   208→        if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n   209→          seen.add(norm);\n   210→          candidates.push({ text: joined3, position: line.index });\n   211→        }\n   212→      }\n   213→    }\n   214→  }\n   215→\n   216→  // Pre-filter to 25 before embedding calls: prefer ALL_CAPS and short candidates.\n   217→  // Position-based scoring handles final ranking.\n   218→  if (candidates.length > 25) {\n   219→    const prioritized = candidates.slice().sort((a, b) => {\n   220→      const aAllCaps = isAllCaps(a.text) ? 0 : 1;\n   221→      const bAllCaps = isAllCaps(b.text) ? 0 : 1;\n   222→      if (aAllCaps !== bAllCaps) return aAllCaps - bAllCaps;\n   223→      const aShort = wordCount(a.text) <= 5 ? 0 : 1;\n   224→      const bShort = wordCount(b.text) <= 5 ? 0 : 1;\n   225→      return aShort - bShort;\n   226→    });\n   227→    return prioritized.slice(0, 25);\n   228→  }\n   229→\n   230→  return candidates;\n   231→}\n   232→\n   233→// Module-level cache for reference embeddings\n   234→let cachedTitleRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\n   235→let cachedHeaderRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\n   236→let cachedNoiseRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\n   237→\n   238→export function _resetEmbeddingCacheForTests(): void {\n   239→  cachedTitleRefEmbedding = null;\n   240→  cachedHeaderRefEmbedding = null;\n   241→  cachedNoiseRefEmbedding = null;\n   242→}\n   243→\n   244→export async function extractTitleWithEmbeddings(\n   245→  text: string,\n   246→  embed: EmbedFn\n   247→): Promise<string | undefined> {\n   248→  if (!text || text.trim().length === 0) {\n   249→    return undefined;\n   250→  }\n   251→\n   252→  const lines = text.split(\"\\n\");\n   253→  const candidates = buildCandidates(lines);\n   254→\n   255→  if (candidates.length === 0) {\n   256→    return undefined;\n   257→  }\n   258→\n   259→  // Cache reference embeddings\n   260→  if (!cachedTitleRefEmbedding) {\n   261→    cachedTitleRefEmbedding = await embed(TITLE_REFERENCE);\n   262→  }\n   263→  if (!cachedHeaderRefEmbedding) {\n   264→    cachedHeaderRefEmbedding = await embed(HEADER_REFERENCE);\n   265→  }\n   266→  if (!cachedNoiseRefEmbedding) {\n   267→    cachedNoiseRefEmbedding = await embed(NOISE_REFERENCE);\n   268→  }\n   269→\n   270→  // Find the first ALL_CAPS candidate with ≥2 words where every word has ≥4 alpha letters.\n   271→  // This structural signal identifies the first clean recipe title heading in cookbook scans.\n   272→  const firstStructuralHeading = candidates.find(\n   273→    (c) =>\n   274→      isAllCaps(c.text) &&\n   275→      wordCount(c.text) >= 2 &&\n   276→      c.text\n   277→        .trim()\n   278→        .split(/\\s+/)\n   279→        .every((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4)\n   280→  );\n   281→\n   282→  const scored: Array<{ text: string; position: number; score: number; rawScore: number }> = [];\n   283→\n   284→  for (const candidate of candidates) {\n   285→    const embedding = await embed(candidate.text);\n   286→    const titleSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedTitleRefEmbedding);\n   287→    const headerSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedHeaderRefEmbedding);\n   288→    const noiseSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedNoiseRefEmbedding);\n   289→    const rawScore = titleSim - Math.max(headerSim, noiseSim);\n   290→\n   291→    // Position factor: multiplicative tiebreaker — amplifies existing signal, doesn't replace it\n   292→    const relativePosition = candidate.position / lines.length;\n   293→    const positionFactor = relativePosition < 0.5\n   294→      ? 1.0 + 0.12 * (1 - relativePosition * 2)\n   295→      : 1.0;\n   296→\n   297→    // ALL_CAPS bonus: recipe books use ALL_CAPS for titles and section headings\n   298→    const allCapsBonus = isAllCaps(candidate.text) && candidate.text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4\n   299→      ? 0.08\n   300→      : 0;\n   301→\n   302→    // Structural heading bonus: first clean ALL_CAPS heading is almost always the recipe title\n   303→    const structuralBonus =\n   304→      firstStructuralHeading && candidate === firstStructuralHeading ? 0.10 : 0;\n   305→\n   306→    const score = rawScore * positionFactor + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n   307→    scored.push({ text: candidate.text, position: candidate.position, score, rawScore });\n   308→  }\n   309→\n   310→  if (scored.length === 0) {\n   311→    return undefined;\n   312→  }\n   313→\n   314→  const bestScore = Math.max(...scored.map((s) => s.score));\n   315→  const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestScore * 0.8);\n   316→\n   317→  // Filter candidates above threshold\n   318→  let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n   319→\n   320→  // Deduplicate: for candidates in a substring relationship, keep the semantically stronger one.\n   321→  // Uses rawScore (pure semantic similarity) rather than final score, because position/bonuses are\n   322→  // ranking tie-breakers — not signals for deciding which overlapping string is the real title.\n   323→  // Rule: keep the longer candidate only when it has strictly higher rawScore (i.e. the longer\n   324→  // string is genuinely more title-like, as happens when a multi-line join completes a title).\n   325→  // When rawScores are equal, keep the shorter (more focused) candidate — in practice this means\n   326→  // a clean title wins over a noisy join that happened to embed identically.\n   327→  selected = selected.filter((a) => {\n   328→    const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n   329→    return !selected.some((b) => {\n   330→      if (b === a) return false;\n   331→      const bLower = b.text.toLowerCase();\n   332→      // b is longer and contains a: remove a only when b is semantically stronger\n   333→      if (bLower.includes(aLower) && b.text.length > a.text.length && b.rawScore > a.rawScore) return true;\n   334→      // b is shorter and is contained in a: remove a when b is equally or more title-like\n   335→      if (aLower.includes(bLower) && b.text.length < a.text.length && b.rawScore >= a.rawScore) return true;\n   336→      return false;\n   337→    });\n   338→  });\n   339→\n   340→  // Multi-title guard: only join multiple candidates with \"+\" when there is\n   341→  // structural evidence of a multi-recipe page (≥2 ALL_CAPS headings).\n   342→  // A single ALL_CAPS title among mixed-case survivors is a single-recipe page —\n   343→  // collapse to the highest-scoring candidate.\n   344→  // Zero ALL_CAPS survivors → mixed-case multi-title page → keep all.\n   345→  if (selected.length > 1) {\n   346→    const allCapsSelected = selected.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n   347→    if (allCapsSelected.length >= 2) {\n   348→      selected = allCapsSelected;\n   349→    } else if (allCapsSelected.length === 1) {\n   350→      selected = [selected.reduce((a, b) => (a.score > b.score ? a : b))];\n   351→    }\n   352→  }\n   353→\n   354→  // Cap at 3, sort by document position\n   355→  selected.sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n   356→  selected = selected.slice(0, 3);\n   357→\n   358→  if (selected.length === 0) {\n   359→    return undefined;\n   360→  }\n   361→\n   362→  return selected.map((s) => s.text).join(\" + \");\n   363→}\n   364→\n   365→/**\n   366→ * Extract potential recipe title from OCR text (sync heuristic fallback)\n   367→ */\n   368→export function extractTitle(text: string): string | undefined {\n   369→  if (!text || text.trim().length === 0) {\n   370→    return undefined;\n   371→  }\n   372→\n   373→  const lines = text.split(\"\\n\").map((line) => line.trim());\n   374→\n   375→  for (const line of lines) {\n   376→    if (line.length === 0) continue;\n   377→    if (line.length < 3 || line.length > 50) continue;\n   378→    if (looksLikeIngredient(line)) continue;\n   379→    if (isAllCaps(line)) continue;\n   380→    if (startsWithNumber(line)) continue;\n   381→    return line;\n   382→  }\n   383→\n   384→  return undefined;\n   385→}\n   386→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5176536c-f5cc-4676-9e25-3601b34e1824","uuid":"e1f42175-014d-482c-a861-915d033ade32","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts","content":"/**\n * Title Extraction\n * Extracts potential recipe title from OCR text using heuristics or semantic embeddings\n */\n\nimport { cosineSimilarity } from \"./embeddings\";\n\nexport type EmbedFn = (text: string) => Promise<Array<number>>;\n\nconst TITLE_REFERENCE =\n  \"recipe name, dish title, name of the food, nazwa przepisu, nazwa dania\";\nconst HEADER_REFERENCE =\n  \"ingredients list, cooking directions, section heading, składniki, przygotowanie, sposób wykonania\";\nconst NOISE_REFERENCE =\n  \"page number, table of contents, book footer, garbled text\";\n\n/**\n * Measurement units commonly found in ingredient lists\n */\nconst MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS = [\n  \"cup\",\n  \"cups\",\n  \"tbsp\",\n  \"tsp\",\n  \"tablespoon\",\n  \"teaspoon\",\n  \"oz\",\n  \"lb\",\n  \"gram\",\n  \"grams\",\n  \"kg\",\n  \"ml\",\n  \"liter\",\n  \"pinch\",\n  \"dash\",\n  \"handful\",\n];\n\n/**\n * Patterns that identify recipe metadata lines (not titles)\n */\nconst METADATA_PATTERNS = [\n  /^(SERVES?|MAKES?|YIELDS?)\\b/i,\n  /^(PREP(ARATION)?|COOK(ING)?|PROOF|RISING|FERMENTATION|REST(ING)?)\\s*(AND\\s*)?(COOK(ING)?)?\\s*TIME/i,\n  /^SAMPLE\\s+SCHEDULE\\b/i,\n  /^BULK\\s+FERMENTATION\\b/i,\n  /^(THIS\\s+RECIPE\\s+)?MAKES\\b/i,\n];\n\n/**\n * Single-word non-title words — standalone OCR fragments unlikely to be recipe titles\n */\nconst NON_TITLE_WORDS = new Set([\n  \"the\", \"and\", \"for\", \"but\", \"not\", \"you\", \"all\", \"can\", \"are\", \"was\",\n  \"has\", \"his\", \"her\", \"its\", \"our\", \"who\", \"how\", \"may\", \"new\", \"now\",\n  \"old\", \"see\", \"way\", \"did\", \"get\", \"let\", \"say\", \"she\", \"too\", \"use\",\n  \"buns\", \"with\",\n]);\n\nfunction looksLikeIngredient(line: string): boolean {\n  const lowerLine = line.toLowerCase();\n  return MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => lowerLine.includes(pattern));\n}\n\nfunction startsWithNumber(line: string): boolean {\n  return /^\\s*\\d/.test(line);\n}\n\nfunction isAllCaps(line: string): boolean {\n  const letters = line.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\");\n  return letters.length > 0 && letters === letters.toUpperCase();\n}\n\nfunction looksLikeMetadata(text: string): boolean {\n  return METADATA_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => pattern.test(text.trim()));\n}\n\nfunction isLikelyGarbled(text: string): boolean {\n  const letters = text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\");\n  if (letters.length < 2) return true;\n\n  // Check vowel ratio — English/Polish text typically has 30–50% vowels\n  const vowels = letters.replace(/[^aeiouAEIOUyYąęóĄĘÓ]/g, \"\").length;\n  const vowelRatio = vowels / letters.length;\n  if (vowelRatio < 0.15 || vowelRatio > 0.85) return true;\n\n  // Single orphaned word ≤3 letters that isn't a common word\n  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n  const COMMON_SHORT = new Set([\n    \"the\", \"and\", \"for\", \"but\", \"not\", \"you\", \"all\", \"can\", \"had\", \"her\",\n    \"was\", \"one\", \"our\", \"out\", \"are\", \"has\", \"his\", \"how\", \"its\", \"may\",\n    \"new\", \"now\", \"old\", \"see\", \"way\", \"who\", \"did\", \"get\", \"let\", \"say\",\n    \"she\", \"too\", \"use\",\n  ]);\n  if (words.length === 1 && letters.length <= 3 && !COMMON_SHORT.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) {\n    return true;\n  }\n\n  // Recipe titles never start with a lowercase letter\n  if (/^[a-z]/.test(text.trim())) {\n    return true;\n  }\n\n  // Mid-text sentence boundary (\". \" followed by a letter) — body text fragment spliced from multiple sentences\n  const trimmed = text.trim();\n  if (/\\.\\s+[a-zA-Z]/.test(trimmed) && !trimmed.endsWith(\")\")) {\n    return true;\n  }\n\n  // Multi-word candidate containing a garbled OCR fragment: a short lowercase word that isn't a known short word\n  if (words.length >= 2) {\n    const commonShort2 = new Set([\n      \"a\", \"i\", \"of\", \"or\", \"to\", \"in\", \"on\", \"is\", \"it\", \"an\",\n      \"as\", \"at\", \"by\", \"do\", \"go\", \"if\", \"no\", \"so\", \"up\", \"we\",\n      \"w\", \"z\",  // Polish prepositions\n    ]);\n    const hasGarbledWord = words.some(\n      (w) =>\n        /^[a-z]/.test(w) &&\n        w.replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\").length <= 2 &&\n        !commonShort2.has(w.toLowerCase())\n    );\n    if (hasGarbledWord) {\n      return true;\n    }\n  }\n\n  return false;\n}\n\nfunction passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n  // Single-word non-title fragments\n  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n  if (words.length === 1 && NON_TITLE_WORDS.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) return false;\n  return true;\n}\n\n/**\n * Detect initial burst of short garbled lines.\n * Returns the index of the first non-garbled or long line.\n */\nfunction findBurstEnd(lines: Array<{ text: string }>): number {\n  let i = 0;\n  while (i < lines.length && lines[i].text.length < 20 && isLikelyGarbled(lines[i].text)) {\n    i++;\n  }\n  return i;\n}\n\nfunction wordCount(text: string): number {\n  return text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.length > 0).length;\n}\n\n/**\n * Build candidate strings from lines: single lines plus multi-line joins (2-3 consecutive).\n * Skips initial burst of short garbled lines. Scans all remaining lines. Caps at 25.\n */\nfunction buildCandidates(\n  lines: Array<string>\n): Array<{ text: string; position: number }> {\n  const nonEmptyLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n\n  for (let i = 0; i < lines.length; i++) {\n    const trimmed = lines[i].trim();\n    if (trimmed.length > 0) {\n      nonEmptyLines.push({ text: trimmed, index: i });\n    }\n  }\n\n  const burstEnd = findBurstEnd(nonEmptyLines);\n  const candidates: Array<{ text: string; position: number }> = [];\n  const seen = new Set<string>();\n\n  for (let i = burstEnd; i < nonEmptyLines.length; i++) {\n    const line = nonEmptyLines[i];\n\n    // Single line\n    if (passesHardFilters(line.text)) {\n      const norm = line.text.toLowerCase();\n      if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n        seen.add(norm);\n        candidates.push({ text: line.text, position: line.index });\n      }\n    }\n\n    // 2-line join\n    if (i + 1 < nonEmptyLines.length) {\n      const joined2 = `${line.text} ${nonEmptyLines[i + 1].text}`;\n      if (passesHardFilters(joined2)) {\n        const norm = joined2.toLowerCase();\n        if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n          seen.add(norm);\n          candidates.push({ text: joined2, position: line.index });\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    // 3-line join\n    if (i + 2 < nonEmptyLines.length) {\n      const joined3 = `${line.text} ${nonEmptyLines[i + 1].text} ${nonEmptyLines[i + 2].text}`;\n      if (passesHardFilters(joined3)) {\n        const norm = joined3.toLowerCase();\n        if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n          seen.add(norm);\n          candidates.push({ text: joined3, position: line.index });\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Pre-filter to 25 before embedding calls: prefer ALL_CAPS and short candidates.\n  // Position-based scoring handles final ranking.\n  if (candidates.length > 25) {\n    const prioritized = candidates.slice().sort((a, b) => {\n      const aAllCaps = isAllCaps(a.text) ? 0 : 1;\n      const bAllCaps = isAllCaps(b.text) ? 0 : 1;\n      if (aAllCaps !== bAllCaps) return aAllCaps - bAllCaps;\n      const aShort = wordCount(a.text) <= 5 ? 0 : 1;\n      const bShort = wordCount(b.text) <= 5 ? 0 : 1;\n      return aShort - bShort;\n    });\n    return prioritized.slice(0, 25);\n  }\n\n  return candidates;\n}\n\n// Module-level cache for reference embeddings\nlet cachedTitleRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\nlet cachedHeaderRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\nlet cachedNoiseRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\n\nexport function _resetEmbeddingCacheForTests(): void {\n  cachedTitleRefEmbedding = null;\n  cachedHeaderRefEmbedding = null;\n  cachedNoiseRefEmbedding = null;\n}\n\nexport async function extractTitleWithEmbeddings(\n  text: string,\n  embed: EmbedFn\n): Promise<string | undefined> {\n  if (!text || text.trim().length === 0) {\n    return undefined;\n  }\n\n  const lines = text.split(\"\\n\");\n  const candidates = buildCandidates(lines);\n\n  if (candidates.length === 0) {\n    return undefined;\n  }\n\n  // Cache reference embeddings\n  if (!cachedTitleRefEmbedding) {\n    cachedTitleRefEmbedding = await embed(TITLE_REFERENCE);\n  }\n  if (!cachedHeaderRefEmbedding) {\n    cachedHeaderRefEmbedding = await embed(HEADER_REFERENCE);\n  }\n  if (!cachedNoiseRefEmbedding) {\n    cachedNoiseRefEmbedding = await embed(NOISE_REFERENCE);\n  }\n\n  // Find the first ALL_CAPS candidate with ≥2 words where every word has ≥4 alpha letters.\n  // This structural signal identifies the first clean recipe title heading in cookbook scans.\n  const firstStructuralHeading = candidates.find(\n    (c) =>\n      isAllCaps(c.text) &&\n      wordCount(c.text) >= 2 &&\n      c.text\n        .trim()\n        .split(/\\s+/)\n        .every((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4)\n  );\n\n  const scored: Array<{ text: string; position: number; score: number; rawScore: number }> = [];\n\n  for (const candidate of candidates) {\n    const embedding = await embed(candidate.text);\n    const titleSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedTitleRefEmbedding);\n    const headerSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedHeaderRefEmbedding);\n    const noiseSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedNoiseRefEmbedding);\n    const rawScore = titleSim - Math.max(headerSim, noiseSim);\n\n    // Position factor: multiplicative tiebreaker — amplifies existing signal, doesn't replace it\n    const relativePosition = candidate.position / lines.length;\n    const positionFactor = relativePosition < 0.5\n      ? 1.0 + 0.12 * (1 - relativePosition * 2)\n      : 1.0;\n\n    // ALL_CAPS bonus: recipe books use ALL_CAPS for titles and section headings\n    const allCapsBonus = isAllCaps(candidate.text) && candidate.text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4\n      ? 0.08\n      : 0;\n\n    // Structural heading bonus: first clean ALL_CAPS heading is almost always the recipe title\n    const structuralBonus =\n      firstStructuralHeading && candidate === firstStructuralHeading ? 0.10 : 0;\n\n    const score = rawScore * positionFactor + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n    scored.push({ text: candidate.text, position: candidate.position, score, rawScore });\n  }\n\n  if (scored.length === 0) {\n    return undefined;\n  }\n\n  const bestScore = Math.max(...scored.map((s) => s.score));\n  const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestScore * 0.8);\n\n  // Filter candidates above threshold\n  let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n\n  // Deduplicate: for candidates in a substring relationship, keep the semantically stronger one.\n  // Uses rawScore (pure semantic similarity) rather than final score, because position/bonuses are\n  // ranking tie-breakers — not signals for deciding which overlapping string is the real title.\n  // Rule: keep the longer candidate only when it has strictly higher rawScore (i.e. the longer\n  // string is genuinely more title-like, as happens when a multi-line join completes a title).\n  // When rawScores are equal, keep the shorter (more focused) candidate — in practice this means\n  // a clean title wins over a noisy join that happened to embed identically.\n  selected = selected.filter((a) => {\n    const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n    return !selected.some((b) => {\n      if (b === a) return false;\n      const bLower = b.text.toLowerCase();\n      // b is longer and contains a: remove a only when b is semantically stronger\n      if (bLower.includes(aLower) && b.text.length > a.text.length && b.rawScore > a.rawScore) return true;\n      // b is shorter and is contained in a: remove a when b is equally or more title-like\n      if (aLower.includes(bLower) && b.text.length < a.text.length && b.rawScore >= a.rawScore) return true;\n      return false;\n    });\n  });\n\n  // Multi-title guard: only join multiple candidates with \"+\" when there is\n  // structural evidence of a multi-recipe page (≥2 ALL_CAPS headings).\n  // A single ALL_CAPS title among mixed-case survivors is a single-recipe page —\n  // collapse to the highest-scoring candidate.\n  // Zero ALL_CAPS survivors → mixed-case multi-title page → keep all.\n  if (selected.length > 1) {\n    const allCapsSelected = selected.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n    if (allCapsSelected.length >= 2) {\n      selected = allCapsSelected;\n    } else if (allCapsSelected.length === 1) {\n      selected = [selected.reduce((a, b) => (a.score > b.score ? a : b))];\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Cap at 3, sort by document position\n  selected.sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n  selected = selected.slice(0, 3);\n\n  if (selected.length === 0) {\n    return undefined;\n  }\n\n  return selected.map((s) => s.text).join(\" + \");\n}\n\n/**\n * Extract potential recipe title from OCR text (sync heuristic fallback)\n */\nexport function extractTitle(text: string): string | undefined {\n  if (!text || text.trim().length === 0) {\n    return undefined;\n  }\n\n  const lines = text.split(\"\\n\").map((line) => line.trim());\n\n  for (const line of lines) {\n    if (line.length === 0) continue;\n    if (line.length < 3 || line.length > 50) continue;\n    if (looksLikeIngredient(line)) continue;\n    if (isAllCaps(line)) continue;\n    if (startsWithNumber(line)) continue;\n    return line;\n  }\n\n  return undefined;\n}\n","numLines":386,"startLine":1,"totalLines":386}}}
