{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QSnLeogHGFHyWp8FPQGdCc","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→2 (/½ cup plus ı tablespoon a sland mixer fried with v for s minutes, or ami tre bad\n     2→nto a loured work counter, t es and shape into ball a a\n     3→3 pan over a medium beat y i both sides. As you cook wre em on top of each other a paper towel to prevent to nd cooling down compic illing onto each Balored, at then fold the cornes in te pe. Serve with sovel.\n     4→DAT FLATBREADS\n     5→le Finnish region of Savo 1a bread, it's more like a : baked in the oven. Often lighter meal with Egg Ba: utely delicious.\n     6→time: I hour\n     7→uttermilk\n     8→shed barley groats\n     9→butter\n    10→rley groats together in mperature overnight.\n    11→ven to 200C400 F\n    12→ng sheet with baking\n    13→its to the buttermilk and mix until con-\n    14→hined. You don't need to use a stand mixer for this dough. Use your hands to spread the dough out onto the prepared baking sheet and bake for about 20 minutes, or until it has a nice colour.\n    15→For image see page 171\n    16→FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\n    17→Maitorieska (Finland)\n    18→Originally this milk-and-barley based flatbread was most common in the Finnish region of Ostroboth-nia, but today can be found pretty much across the whole country. Eat it fresh with some butter on the side and a glass of milk to drink next to it.\n    19→Preparation and cooking time: 1 hour\n    20→Makes: 8-10 pieces\n    21→500 ml/17 fl oz (2 cups plus 2 tablespoons) milk\n    22→7g/0.24 oz (½ tablespoon) salt\n    23→500g/1 Ib 2 oz (3 cups) barley flour\n    24→60 g/2¼ oz (½ cup) plain (all-purpose) flour butter, to serve\n    25→Preheat the oven to at least 250°C/480°F/Gas Mark 9, up to 350°C/660°F/highest gas mark if you can.\n    26→Mix all of the ingredients together in a bowl. The dough should be quite firm.\n    27→Divide the dough into 8-10 equal pieces. Knead the individual pieces by hand for a little while, then shape them into round flatbreads using your hands. They should be about 1 cm/½ inch thick.\n    28→Put the flatbreads on a baking sheet and prick them all over with a fork. Bake for 8-10 minutes, depending on how hot the oven is. Serve warm with butter.\n    29→FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\n    30→Perunarieska (Finland)\n    31→This soft and quite thick Finnish potato flatbread is often eaten warm with some salty butter spread on top. Perfect to make if you have leftover mashed potatoes.\n    32→Preparation and cooking time: 30 minutes\n    33→Makes: 10 flatbreads\n    34→5g/0.20 oz (1 teaspoon) salt\n    35→I egg\n    36→180 g/6½ oz (1½ cups) plain (all-purpose) flour\n    37→250g/9 oz (1 cup) leftover mashed potatoes butter, to serve\n    38→Preheat the oven to 250°C/480°F/Gas Mark 9 and line a baking sheet with baking (parchment) paper.\n    39→Add the salt, egg and flour to the mashed potatoes in a bowl and mix until it is a smooth dough.\n    40→Divide the dough into Io equal pieces and flatten them with your hands into quite thin, round breads.\n    41→Put the breads on the prepared baking sheet and bake for 8-Io minutes, or until the breads are nicely golden. Enjoy them warm from the oven with butter.\n    42→For image see page 171\n    43→175 Recipes / Flatbreads"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01CbC4rJHCgURqQuw13Pnwgp","session_id":"5176536c-f5cc-4676-9e25-3601b34e1824","uuid":"b582d21e-87ab-458d-bf9f-a0cc10fef1b0"}
