{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018P9C7nEY3jAZB6Gd2WJbXJ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→2 (/½ cup plus ı tablespoon a sland mixer fried with v for s minutes, or ami tre bad\n     2→nto a loured work counter, t es and shape into ball a a\n     3→3 pan over a medium beat y i both sides. As you cook wre em on top of each other a paper towel to prevent to nd cooling down compic illing onto each Balored, at then fold the cornes in te pe. Serve with sovel.\n     4→DAT FLATBREADS\n     5→le Finnish region of Savo 1a bread, it's more like a : baked in the oven. Often lighter meal with Egg Ba: utely delicious.\n     6→time: I hour\n     7→uttermilk\n     8→shed barley groats\n     9→butter\n    10→rley groats together in mperature overnight.\n    11→ven to 200C400 F\n    12→ng sheet with baking\n    13→its to the buttermilk and mix until con-\n    14→hined. You don't need to use a stand mixer for this dough. Use your hands to spread the dough out onto the prepared baking sheet and bake for about 20 minutes, or until it has a nice colour.\n    15→For image see page 171\n    16→FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\n    17→Maitorieska (Finland)\n    18→Originally this milk-and-barley based flatbread was most common in the Finnish region of Ostroboth-nia, but today can be found pretty much across the whole country. Eat it fresh with some butter on the side and a glass of milk to drink next to it.\n    19→Preparation and cooking time: 1 hour\n    20→Makes: 8-10 pieces\n    21→500 ml/17 fl oz (2 cups plus 2 tablespoons) milk\n    22→7g/0.24 oz (½ tablespoon) salt\n    23→500g/1 Ib 2 oz (3 cups) barley flour\n    24→60 g/2¼ oz (½ cup) plain (all-purpose) flour butter, to serve\n    25→Preheat the oven to at least 250°C/480°F/Gas Mark 9, up to 350°C/660°F/highest gas mark if you can.\n    26→Mix all of the ingredients together in a bowl. The dough should be quite firm.\n    27→Divide the dough into 8-10 equal pieces. Knead the individual pieces by hand for a little while, then shape them into round flatbreads using your hands. They should be about 1 cm/½ inch thick.\n    28→Put the flatbreads on a baking sheet and prick them all over with a fork. Bake for 8-10 minutes, depending on how hot the oven is. Serve warm with butter.\n    29→FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\n    30→Perunarieska (Finland)\n    31→This soft and quite thick Finnish potato flatbread is often eaten warm with some salty butter spread on top. Perfect to make if you have leftover mashed potatoes.\n    32→Preparation and cooking time: 30 minutes\n    33→Makes: 10 flatbreads\n    34→5g/0.20 oz (1 teaspoon) salt\n    35→I egg\n    36→180 g/6½ oz (1½ cups) plain (all-purpose) flour\n    37→250g/9 oz (1 cup) leftover mashed potatoes butter, to serve\n    38→Preheat the oven to 250°C/480°F/Gas Mark 9 and line a baking sheet with baking (parchment) paper.\n    39→Add the salt, egg and flour to the mashed potatoes in a bowl and mix until it is a smooth dough.\n    40→Divide the dough into Io equal pieces and flatten them with your hands into quite thin, round breads.\n    41→Put the breads on the prepared baking sheet and bake for 8-Io minutes, or until the breads are nicely golden. Enjoy them warm from the oven with butter.\n    42→For image see page 171\n    43→175 Recipes / Flatbreads"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5176536c-f5cc-4676-9e25-3601b34e1824","uuid":"d94ccade-5aed-47c3-b24c-dd631a59f723","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/input/FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS.real.txt","content":"2 (/½ cup plus ı tablespoon a sland mixer fried with v for s minutes, or ami tre bad\nnto a loured work counter, t es and shape into ball a a\n3 pan over a medium beat y i both sides. As you cook wre em on top of each other a paper towel to prevent to nd cooling down compic illing onto each Balored, at then fold the cornes in te pe. Serve with sovel.\nDAT FLATBREADS\nle Finnish region of Savo 1a bread, it's more like a : baked in the oven. Often lighter meal with Egg Ba: utely delicious.\ntime: I hour\nuttermilk\nshed barley groats\nbutter\nrley groats together in mperature overnight.\nven to 200C400 F\nng sheet with baking\nits to the buttermilk and mix until con-\nhined. You don't need to use a stand mixer for this dough. Use your hands to spread the dough out onto the prepared baking sheet and bake for about 20 minutes, or until it has a nice colour.\nFor image see page 171\nFINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\nMaitorieska (Finland)\nOriginally this milk-and-barley based flatbread was most common in the Finnish region of Ostroboth-nia, but today can be found pretty much across the whole country. Eat it fresh with some butter on the side and a glass of milk to drink next to it.\nPreparation and cooking time: 1 hour\nMakes: 8-10 pieces\n500 ml/17 fl oz (2 cups plus 2 tablespoons) milk\n7g/0.24 oz (½ tablespoon) salt\n500g/1 Ib 2 oz (3 cups) barley flour\n60 g/2¼ oz (½ cup) plain (all-purpose) flour butter, to serve\nPreheat the oven to at least 250°C/480°F/Gas Mark 9, up to 350°C/660°F/highest gas mark if you can.\nMix all of the ingredients together in a bowl. The dough should be quite firm.\nDivide the dough into 8-10 equal pieces. Knead the individual pieces by hand for a little while, then shape them into round flatbreads using your hands. They should be about 1 cm/½ inch thick.\nPut the flatbreads on a baking sheet and prick them all over with a fork. Bake for 8-10 minutes, depending on how hot the oven is. Serve warm with butter.\nFINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\nPerunarieska (Finland)\nThis soft and quite thick Finnish potato flatbread is often eaten warm with some salty butter spread on top. Perfect to make if you have leftover mashed potatoes.\nPreparation and cooking time: 30 minutes\nMakes: 10 flatbreads\n5g/0.20 oz (1 teaspoon) salt\nI egg\n180 g/6½ oz (1½ cups) plain (all-purpose) flour\n250g/9 oz (1 cup) leftover mashed potatoes butter, to serve\nPreheat the oven to 250°C/480°F/Gas Mark 9 and line a baking sheet with baking (parchment) paper.\nAdd the salt, egg and flour to the mashed potatoes in a bowl and mix until it is a smooth dough.\nDivide the dough into Io equal pieces and flatten them with your hands into quite thin, round breads.\nPut the breads on the prepared baking sheet and bake for 8-Io minutes, or until the breads are nicely golden. Enjoy them warm from the oven with butter.\nFor image see page 171\n175 Recipes / Flatbreads","numLines":43,"startLine":1,"totalLines":43}}}
